# Render static-site cache headers.
# Format: one URL pattern per block, indented header lines beneath it.
# Render and Netlify both honor this `_headers` syntax for static sites.
#
# Strategy:
#   * HTML / JS / CSS  → no-cache, must-revalidate. We have no
#     content-addressed assets (no hashed filenames, no `?v=` busters), so
#     long max-age would pin stale code on the user's machine after every
#     deploy. `no-cache` still allows ETag/Last-Modified revalidation —
#     the browser sends If-None-Match and the server returns 304 with no
#     body. This is the common static-site pattern when filenames don't
#     change.
#   * Chunk JSON / binary payloads under /tsne_chunks/  → 1 day public
#     cache. These are content snapshots of the corpus; they only change
#     when the data pipeline re-runs (rare), and at ~20 MB per chunk
#     × 51 chunks the cumulative cost of revalidating on every page load
#     is the worst hit on the deployed app. A 24h max-age with
#     `stale-while-revalidate` lets the browser serve from cache instantly
#     while quietly checking for updates in the background.
#   * Interview payloads + tsne_payload.json → same 1-day rule.

/*.html
  Cache-Control: no-cache, must-revalidate

/*.js
  Cache-Control: no-cache, must-revalidate

/*.css
  Cache-Control: no-cache, must-revalidate

/tsne_chunks/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400, stale-while-revalidate=604800

/interviews/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400, stale-while-revalidate=604800

/tsne_payload.json
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=86400, stale-while-revalidate=604800
